<br>
Althought Hera was a goddess of both marraige and childbirth, sh enever had a happy or peacefull marriage. Zeus continued to have love affairs with Goddesse's, Nymphs, and mortals long after he married Hera, much to her chagrin.<br>
<br>
A full accounting of his conquests would humble Don Juan- or even Walt Chamberlin. The list of trysts included, amoung many, and many others:<br>
<br>
<br>
Maia: a Pleiad ( daughter of Atlas ) , by whom he fathered Hermes<br>
<br>
Electra: another Pleiad, with whom he conceived Dardanus<br>
<br>
Taygete: a third Pleiad, with whom he concieved Lacedaemon<br>
<br>
Semele: a mortal, who gave birth to Dionysus<br>
<br>
Alcmene, another mortal, who became the mother of Heracles.<br>
<br>
Danae, the mother of Perseus<br>
<br>
Leda: by whom he fathered Helen and Polydeuces<br>
<br>
Zeus also had dalliances with boys, the most notable of which was Ganymede, a beautiful young trojan whom Zeus abducted to become his cup-bearer.<br>
<br>
Needless to say, this parade of paramours caused quite a bit of marital tension between the King and Queen of Heaven. Hera was understandably jealous of all of her husbands infidelities. The Goddess had a violent temper, and Zeus roused her fury more then once with his incessant seductions.<br>
<br>
The scorned Goddess poured most of her energy into pursuing, punishing, and persecuting her husbands mistresses and basterd children.:<br>
<br>
She tried to prevent Leto from giving birth even though that affair had come BEFORE his marriage<br>
<br>
She sent a relentless gadfly to tourment the mortal Io after Zeus had changed her into a cow.<br>
<br>
She provoked Artemis into shooting and killing Callisto, whom Zeus had transformed into a bear.<br>
<br>
She killed nearly all the inhabitants of the island named after Aegina ( though Zeus later repopulated the island by transforming ants into people )<br>
<br>
She goaded Semele into making a request to Zeus that ultimitly destroyed her.<br>
<br>
She relentlessly persecuted Zeus's mortal son, Heracles, who rose to immortal staus in spite of her.<br>
<br>
Jealousy was not the only emotion that could rouse Hera's anger. The goddess was also extremely competitive about her beauty. When Side, the the first wife of the great hunter Orion, boasted that she was more beautiful then Hera, the goddess immediatly sent her to Hades. And when Paris of Troy claimed Aphrodite the fairest of the goddesses, Hera naturally took the side of the Greeks in the trojan that followed. Zeus forbade divine interfearance in this conflict.Yet despite this prohabition, Hera once seduced her husband, distracting his attention so that Poseidon could incite the Greeks to attack the Trojans.<br>
<br>
Zeus and Hera once again argued about whether men or women derived greater pleasure from the act of making love. Each insisted that the other's gender reaped the greater share of pleasure. The great Seer Teiresias, called in to decide the matter, insisted that a woman's pleasure was nine times that of a man. Infuriated, Hera immediatly blinded the seer.<br>
<br>
<br>
