<br>
TURF WARS.<br>
<br>
Poseidon, who wn the right to rule to seas, was also god of horses and earth-quakes. Poseidon's domain actually extended beyond the oceans to include freshwater rivers, even though the river gods were sons of Oceanus and Tethys.<br>
<br>
Mythmakers often depict Poseidon as gruff and quick to anger. He sometimes resented the greater dominion of Zeus. Perhaps for this reason, Poseidon lived not in Olympus, but in an underwater palace off the eastern coast of Greece.<br>
<br>
His subordinate position to Zeus made him sensitive about his other rights. Poseidon got into more fights over city patronage then any other Olympian. He contested the patronage of Argos with Hera and the patronage of Corinth with Helius. Poseidon lost both disputes and had to content himself with the patronage of various islands and seaports.<br>
<br>
The most famous of these disputes was the fight over Athens with Athena. Poseidon claimed teh land by plunging his trident into the ground of the acropolis and creating a salt water spring. But Athena later planted the first olive tree besides the well and claimed the city as her own. Poseidon immediatly challenged her to combat, but Zeus intervened and put the matter before the divine tribunal. Wishing to remain neutral on both sides and above the fray, Zeus did not vote. That left four other gods, who all voted for Poseidon. ( Hades,as was his custom, did not attend the Olympian hearing ) The five goddesses, however, all sided with Athena, giving her the right to the land by virtue of her greater gift to the city.<br>
<br>
Ina  fury, Poseidon flooded the Attic plain. The Athenians adopted several measures to appease Poseidons wrath. The city denied the women of Athens the right to vote. It ended the practise of men carrying on thier mothers names. And all Athenians continued to honor both Poseidon and Athena on the Acropolis. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#336699><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/ugoddessartemis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goddess Artemis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Bronze Warrior</span><br>  Posts: 185<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(9/30/01 3:51:00 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/mogoddessartemis/images/triplemoon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Beastly Couplings, Beastly Children:</span><hr size=1> Poseidon courted Amphitrite, one of the Nereids ( daughter of Nereus, the Old Man of the sea ). Yet Amphitrite scorned the god's advances and fled to the Atlas Mountains. Poseidon refused to give up and sent messangers after her to plead his case. One of these, Delphinus, argued so persuasively for his master that he broke down Amphitrite's resistance. She agreed to marry Poseidon. ( The god later showed his gratitude by placing his messanger's image in the sky known as a constellation: the Dolphin. )<br>
<br>
Like his brother Zeus, however, Poseidon was not exactly th poster boy for fidelity. He too had numerous affairs with goddesses, nymphs, and mortals. Like most sea gods, Poseidon had the power to transform his shape, and often did so in order to complete a seduction:<br>
<br>
He appeared to the maiden Medusa as a bird. Unfortunitly, he chose as the setting for this seduction one of Athena's temples. The enraged Goddess punished Medusa by turning her into a Gorgon.<br>
<br>
To mate with Theophane, whom he had changed into a ewe in order to hide her from her many suitors, he transformed himself into a ram.<br>
<br>
When Demeter, overwhelmed by the loss of her daughter Persephone, attempted to escape he rbrothers attentions by changing herself into a mare, Poseidon was not fooled. He changed himself into a stallion and mated with her in an Arcadian pasture.<br>
<br>
Poseidon also mated in the shape of a Dolphin and a bull. These many transformations had a powerful influence on his offspring too:<br>
<br>
Medusa's children were the winged horse Pegasus and the giant warrior Chysaor.<br>
<br>
His union with Theophane produced the famous golden fleeced ram<br>
<br>
Demeter had two children by him: the nymph Despoena and a wild and remarkable horse named Arion.<br>
<br>
Many of his children were giants, including Chrysaor , the cyclopes Polyphemus, and the trouble making brothers Otus and Ephialtes.<br>
<br>
As a father, Poseidon was very protective , not only towards his three children by Amphitrite, but towards the children of his many mistresses, too. Poseidon made his son Cycnus invulnerable to weapons. He helped Theseus prove his parantage in a bragging contest with King Minos of Crete. And he avenged the blinding of Polyphemus by tourmenting Odysseus for 10 years.<br>
<br>
Perhaps because he mated witha  goddess in that form, the horse became sacred to Poseidon. Some storytellers insisted that he invented the horse by smashing his trident down upon a rock. In any case, it is said that he invented horse racing and perhaps the bridle as well. Whereever he went, he rode in a gold chariot drawn by two magnificant white horses with golden mares and brass hooves. <p>Goddess Artemis
Protector of the Amazons
