Protector of the Amazons
~*~Goddess of the hunt and the Moon~*~</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003366><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/ugoddessartemis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goddess Artemis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Bronze Warrior</span><br>  Posts: 189<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(10/2/01 12:11:26 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/mogoddessartemis/images/triplemoon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Home is where the Hearth is</span><hr size=1> The first born of the six children of Rhea and Cronus, Hestia was the kindest, most virtious, and most charitable of all teh Olympian Goddesses and Gods. As goddess of the hearth and fire-the symbolic center of the home- Hestia watched over the home, household activities, and the family. Indeed, sonme storytellers assert that Hestia herself invented the art of building houses. By extension, she also protected teh community, the civic affairs of the communal family.<br>
<br>
Unlike most other gods and goddesses, Hestia had few shrines built to honor her. But she needed none, for every home was her shrine-as well as the public hearth of every city. Suppliants could seek her protection in any private home  or in the city hall.<br>
<br>
The goddess of the home and family never had a family of her own. At one time, both Poseidon and the younger god Apollo pursued her, and the competition for her favor threatened to get ugly. But her supreme dedication to peace never allowed Hestia to take part in wars, rivalries, or other disputes. So in order to maintain peace on Olympus, Hestia turned down both rivals and sword by Zeus's head to maintain her chastity forever. Thereafter she withstood all amourus advances by gods, Titans, and mortals alike. Zeus rewarded her for this sacrifice by guaranteeing her the honor of recieveing the first portion of every public sacrifice. <p>Goddess Artemis
Protector of the Amazons
~*~Goddess of the hunt and the Moon~*~</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#336699><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/ugoddessartemis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goddess Artemis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Bronze Warrior</span><br>  Posts: 190<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(10/2/01 12:43:05 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/mogoddessartemis/images/triplemoon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Earth Angel</span><hr size=1> Although the divison of kingdoms amoung the three sons of Cronus left earth as common ground, if anyone on Olympus ruled over earth, it was Demeter. The goddess of the harvest, earth and fertility. Demeter persided over all crops, but especially grains. ( For some reason , she was not fond of beans, regarding them as impure. )<br>
<br>
Like her sister Hestia, Demeter never married, but she did have several love affairs. With her first love Zeus, Demeter had two children, a daughter named Kore ( later called Persephone ): and a son, Iacchus.<br>
<br>
At the marriage of Ares's daughter Harmonia and Cadmus, the first King of Thebes, Demeter fell in love for the second time: with brides brother, Iasion, a Titan. The couple lay together in a thrice-plowed field. But when the lovers returned tot eh weeding feast, Zeus spotted the mud on thier arms and legs and jealously killed Iasion on the spot with a thunderbolt. Her child by Iasion, Plutus, would become the god of the earths wealth.<br>
<br>
For most part, Demeter was gently and mild. Very rarely however, she exploded with anger. Her most notible outburst of anger came in the wake of her daughter Persephone's abduction by Hades. In her thirst for vengance-and her sorrow-Demeter made the earth barren, forbidding tree's to blossom and crops to grow and creating a year-long famine.<br>
<br>
Even in teh throes of despair, however, Demeter responded to kindness with kindness and generocity of her own. In the midst of her search for her daughter. The daughters of Celeus, king of Eleusis, invited Demeter - who was disguesed as an old woman- to stay in thier palace. In return for this kindness, Demeter schooled Celeus and the Eleusinians in the religious rites in her honor that came to be known as the Eleusinian Mysteries-the most widespread and influential of all Greek religious rites.<br>
<br>
Queen Meteneira offered Demeter a place in her home, asking the old woman to serve as her sons nurse. Demeter adored the young boy, Demophon, and - due to her gratitude to his parents and he rlove for the boy-wanted to give teh gift of immortality. But Meteneira was horrified to discover teh old woman in the act of laying the baby on the embers at night to smoother out his mortality. As a result, Demeter never got the chance to complete the rite.<br>
<br>
Demeter also rewarded Triptolemus, an Eleusinian ( perhaps another son of Celeus ) who gave her the first clue to her daughters wearabouts. Thanks to him, Demeter taught him the art of agriculture. She then sent him throughout the world with seed corn, a wooden plough, and her dragon-drawn cahriot to sow these lessons everywhere. <p>Goddess Artemis
Protector of the Amazons
~*~Goddess of the hunt and the Moon~*~</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003366><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/ugoddessartemis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goddess Artemis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Bronze Warrior</span><br>  Posts: 191<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(10/2/01 12:47:17 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/mogoddessartemis/images/triplemoon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> SUMMERY</span><hr size=1> Zeus ruled, for the most part, with wisom and fairness<br>
<br>
Hera was jealous- with good cause- of her husbands countless affairs. She often tourmented his mistresses and there children. She also led a rebellion against Zeus, but failed.<br>
<br>
Poseidon , god of the sea, often looked for ways to expand his influence<br>
<br>
Hades, lord of the dead, actually preferred the darkness of the Underworld to all other places.<br>
<br>
Hestia, virginal goddess of hearth and home , tried to keep the peace amoung families and communities- even amoung the Olympians.<br>
<br>
Demeter, goddess of the harvest, was kind and generous-but if crossed, imposed harsh punishments. <p>Goddess Artemis
Protector of the Amazons
