<br>
Zeus, of course, continued to rule the roost amoung this expanded pantheon, and No wonder: He was brother or father to 9 of the other 11 Olympians. Not counting Hades, who was not considered an Olympian, Zeus had four siblings on Olympus: Poseidon, Hera, Hestia and Demeter. But he also fathered Ares ( by Hera ) , Athena ( by Metis ) Artemis and Apollo ( by Leto ) and Hermes ( by Maia ). Zeus woudl also father Dionysus ( by Semele ),a  god who would later take his place amoung the pantheon. <p>Goddess Artemis
Protector of the Amazons
~*~Goddess of the hunt and the Moon~*~</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003366><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/ugoddessartemis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goddess Artemis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Bronze Warrior</span><br>  Posts: 193<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(10/2/01 1:27:09 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/mogoddessartemis/images/triplemoon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> First in War, First in Peace : Athena</span><hr size=1> Of all the Olympians, few enjoyed teh universal respect accorded to Athena-the Virgin goddess of arts, crafts, and war. Athena was also the goddess of wisdom, which in her case, meant the technical skill of artisans adn craftsmen as well as practical sense and cunning.<br>
<br>
As Goddess of Arts and Crafts, Athena recieved credit for inventing many usefull tools and arts. Athena introduced teh plow,rake, yoke, and bridle to farmers. She also invented teh chariot and designed the first ship. Her other inventions included the earthenware pot, the flute, and the trumpet. In addition, Athena first taught the science of mathematics as well as such household arts as spinning, weaving, and cooking. <p>Goddess Artemis
Protector of the Amazons
~*~Goddess of the hunt and the Moon~*~</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#336699><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/ugoddessartemis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goddess Artemis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Bronze Warrior</span><br>  Posts: 194<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(10/2/01 11:46:51 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/mogoddessartemis/images/triplemoon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A sure fire way for a migraine : Athena's Birth</span><hr size=1> Athena, you'll recall had not yet been born when her father Zeus swallowed Metis, her mother. Zeus did not fear Athena, though it was foretold that her wisdom and strength would match his own. But he dared not risk the birth of a second child by Metis, a son destined to usurp his position.<br>
<br>
After swallowing Metis, Zeus did not give a second thought to his child by her. But one day as he walked along the shore of Lake Tritonis, Zeus was suddenly racked with a splitting headach. He suffered from such pain that he roared in agony.<br>
<br>
Unable to bear the pain, Zeus called upon either Hephaestus or Prometheus, who brought  an ax down upon his head, splitting open his skull. Dressed in full armour, an adult Athena emerged from her father's head with a shout that echoed throughout the world.<br>
<br>
The borth of Athena completed the evolution from a mother-dominated mythology to one dominated by a supream patriach: Zeus. Though two generations, mothers had controlled the power structure of the immortals. In leauge with thier sons, these mothers had toppled thier mates. First Gaia had conspired with her son Cronus to castrate Uranus. Next Rhea-with Gaia's help-had saved her son Zeus in order to overthrow Cronus.<br>
<br>
Zeus ended this pattern, however, by swallowing Metis and the unborn Athena. In appropriating the female function of giving birth, Zeus ended the line of female supremecy. For Athena, born out of Zeus's head, owed no loyalty to any mother.<br>
 <p>Goddess Artemis
Protector of the Amazons
~*~Goddess of the hunt and the Moon~*~</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003366><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/ugoddessartemis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goddess Artemis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Bronze Warrior</span><br>  Posts: 195<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(10/2/01 11:56:41 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/mogoddessartemis/images/triplemoon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> War ! What is it good for?</span><hr size=1> The goddess of war, unlike her half brother Ares, god of war, had little taste for blood. Though often depicted in full armour-helmeted, with spear and shield- Athena derived more pleasure from peaceful resolutions of disputes then from battle. In keeping with her aversions to bloodlust, Athena was also merciful. When seated on teh tribunal that tried Orestes for murdering his mother after she had murdered his father, for example, Athena voted for aquittal.<br>
<br>
Though she shunned warfare, however, when forced into battle, she proved nearly invincible. A brilliant strategist, she twice defeated the war god Ares on the battlefield. She also was a dominant force in the war with the giants.<br>
<br>
The goddess of both war and wisdom often awarded those who demonstrated bravery or ingenuity. For instance, she helped Perseus ( anothe rchild of Zeus ) kill the Gorgon Medusa. Afterward, she proudly displayed teh ehad of teh Gorgon in the center of her shield.<br>
<br>
Athena also acted as Odysseus's speacial protector. When the hero finally arrived back home in Ithaca after 20 years, Athena-though in disguise-appeared to greet him. Odysseus returned the favor of her deceit by lying about who he was. With a laugh, Athena revealed her true identity and admitted that her and Odysseus were two of a kind, shrewed liars both. <p>Goddess Artemis
Protector of the Amazons
~*~Goddess of the hunt and the Moon~*~</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#336699><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/ugoddessartemis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goddess Artemis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Bronze Warrior</span><br>  Posts: 196<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(10/3/01 11:25:19 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/mogoddessartemis/images/triplemoon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A not so immaculate conception</span><hr size=1> A virginal goddess, Athena remained chaste despite many potential suitors. During the Trojan War, however, she experianced a close call.<br>
<br>
Athena needed both armour and weapons, for she went without them except when in battle. So she asked Hephaestus to forge some for her, which he gladly offered as a labor of love.<br>
<br>
Athena apparently didn't appreciate the import of these words. When she entered teh shop to check on his progress, Hephaestus-normally deferential towards the goddesses-attacked her. Poseidon had apparently played a trick on him, telling the smith god that Athena yearned for him to make passionate love to her.<br>
<br>
Athena quickly pulled her self away from her attacker, but Hephaestus could not stop himself: His seed spilled out onto her thigh. Athena, greatly offended, took some wool and wiped off teh god's semen.<br>
<br>
Whens he tossed teh wool to the ground however, she unwittlingly fertilized Gaia. The earth goddess-disgusted by this tale of violation-disavowed any responcibility for the offspring of this misadventure. So Athena vowed to care for the baby herself. The infant, Erichthonius, would grow up to become the first king of Athens to worship Athena. <p>Goddess Artemis
Protector of the Amazons
~*~Goddess of the hunt and the Moon~*~</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003366><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/ugoddessartemis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goddess Artemis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Bronze Warrior</span><br>  Posts: 197<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(10/3/01 11:31:35 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/mogoddessartemis/images/triplemoon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Three's a crowd: The Olympian Love Triangle</span><hr size=1> A times, Mount Olympus bore a resemblance to that later hotbed of intrique and betrayal: Melrose Place. Start with Zeus, who fathered 5 Olympians-with four different mates! Add Hera, the archetypal jealous wife, constantly trying to catch her husband and plotting against his mistresses and his children by them. Don't forget the sibling rivalry between the three brothers-or that Hera's sister Demeter also slept with Zeus.<br>
<br>
The second generation Olympians was not exempt from participating in this soap opera. Hermes would steal from his half-brother Apollo. Hephaestus would immobilize his mother Hera. And Aphrodite would make love to no less then 4 of the six gods on Olympus. Naturally, this created some tension-especially between her and her husband, Hephaestus. <p>Goddess Artemis
Protector of the Amazons
~*~Goddess of the hunt and the Moon~*~</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#336699><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/ugoddessartemis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goddess Artemis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Bronze Warrior</span><br>  Posts: 198<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(10/3/01 11:37:51 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/mogoddessartemis/images/triplemoon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The Heavenly castoff: Hephaestus</span><hr size=1> Hephaestus, the god of smithing, metalworking, and craftsmanship, was born of the rivalry between Hera and Zeus. Hera furiously jealous when Athena burst out of his husbands head, decided that if he could do it, so could she. So Hera resolved to bear her own child without his help. Sadly, the child, Hephaestus, was born sickly and lame. Hera, disgusted and embarassed by her creation, thre the child out of heaven. Hephaestus landed on teh greek island of Lemnos, where he worked at his craft and became a briliant artsian. <p>Goddess Artemis
Protector of the Amazons
~*~Goddess of the hunt and the Moon~*~</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003366><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/ugoddessartemis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goddess Artemis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Bronze Warrior</span><br>  Posts: 199<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(10/3/01 11:47:59 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/mogoddessartemis/images/triplemoon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Heavenly castoff: Hephaestus: continued</span><hr size=1> Having become a master craftsman, hephaestus won his way back into heaven by forging a magnificant golden throne for his decidedly unmaternal mother. Hephaestus was not hoping to win he rfavor, however, but rather to punish her for the ill treatment of him. As soon as she sat in it, teh chair held her tight.<br>
<br>
The Gods and Goddesses pleaded with Hephaestus to forgive his mother and even invited the exile back to Olympus. Still he would not release her. Finally, Dionysus got Hephaestus drunk and persuaded him to let his mother go.<br>
<br>
Welcomed back to Olympus, Hephaestus quickly made himself indispensable. An ingenious artist and artisan, he created countless beautiful , intricate, and often indestructable objects. The hands of Hephaestus created ( amoung many other works) :<br>
<br>
All the palaces of the Olympian gods<br>
<br>
The shield of Achillies<br>
<br>
Pandora, the first woman<br>
<br>
Some say that he constructed many mechanical creatures of gold-including the worlds first robots!- to help him with his work. He also built three legged tables with golden wheels that moved themselves around his workshop. Whenever the Olympians met, these wondourus table would run to the meeting place and then run back again afterward. <p>Goddess Artemis
Protector of the Amazons
~*~Goddess of the hunt and the Moon~*~</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#336699><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/ugoddessartemis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goddess Artemis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Bronze Warrior</span><br>  Posts: 200<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(10/4/01 12:00:05 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/mogoddessartemis/images/triplemoon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Fear and Loathing on Mount Olympus: Ares</span><hr size=1> Hera had another son-this one with Zeus-who became one of the exalted of Olympus: Ares, God of war. But Ares quickly became the ost hated amoung the gods. All immortals loathed him, with three exceptions:<br>
<br>
Eris, goddess of discord < Some storytellers say Eris was twin sister of Ares >, appreciated the way he took her work to a new level.<br>
<br>
Hades didn't necessarily like Ares, but recogonized that he was good for business in the Underworld.<br>
<br>
Aphrodite loved him<br>
<br>
Treu, Ares was brave and strong-but he was also argumentive, impulsive, bloodthirsty, and destructive. In conflicts, the god of war chose sides capriciously and sometimes even switched sides in the middle of a war. Ares simply took pleasure in the bloodshed, slaughter, and wanton destruction of war.<br>
<br>
Ironically, teh god of war was not so skillful as a warrior:<br>
<br>
Level headed, disciplined Athena bested him twice.<br>
<br>
Otus and Ephialtes, the giant sons of Poseidon, also defeated him. Indeed, they humiliated him, trapping him inside a bronze jar  for over a year before Hermes manged to set him free.<br>
<br>
Heracles knocked the god of war off his feet four times in a single battle and ultimatly forced him to flee from the battle field.<br>
<br>
Diomedes stabbed him witha  spear and sent him running from the battlefield outside Troy.<br>
<br>
Ares never married, but he fathered dozens of children with both mortals and immortals. The most notable of these many mistresses was teh goddess of love: Aphrodite. <p>Goddess Artemis
Protector of the Amazons
~*~Goddess of the hunt and the Moon~*~</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#003366><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/ugoddessartemis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goddess Artemis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Bronze Warrior</span><br>  Posts: 201<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(10/5/01 1:38:50 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/mogoddessartemis/images/triplemoon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> First of the Red hot lovers: Aphrodite</span><hr size=1> Aphrodite, as noted earlier, actually predated Zeus and the other Olympians. She rose from the sea foam created when Cronus-the father of the Olympians-threw Uranus's severed genitals into the sea.<br>
<br>
The Goddess of love, lust, and mating never had to do a bit of work. Indeed, she had no other responcibility but to make love-and that, she did with abandon.<br>
<br>
Aphrodire, who possessed a magicgirdle that made its wearer an object of desire for everyone who saw her, was always happy to help young lovers. She took particular delight in causing her fellow Olympians to fall in love with mortals.<br>
 ( Zeus paid her back in kind by making her fall in love with the mortal Anchises-and concieve the hero Aeneas )<br>
<br>
Like the other gods and goddesses, however, Aphrodite also harshly punished those who refused to honor her properly.<br>
( In this case, it meant celibats or others who withstood the pleasures of love.)<br>
Hippolytus was just one of the mortals whom Aphrodite punished for denying himself of erotic joys. <p>Goddess Artemis
Protector of the Amazons
~*~Goddess of the hunt and the Moon~*~</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#336699><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub11.ezboard.com/ugoddessartemis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goddess Artemis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Bronze Warrior</span><br>  Posts: 203<br> <font color=#FFFF33>(10/6/01 5:20:51 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/mogoddessartemis/images/triplemoon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A fine romance?</span><hr size=1> Hera, reconciled with her son Hephaestus, arranged for him to marry the goddess of love. Zeus, Aphrodite's adoptive father, agreed. Unsurprisingly, the marriage of the enchantingly beautiful, sensual, and insatiable Aphrodite and the powerful, but gruff, ugly, and lame Hephaestus was not a happy one. Aphrodite could not confine her love to just one other. The goddess did not remain faithful to Hephaestus-not by a long shot. She had countless affairs with both gods and mortals.<br>
<br>
The most long-standing and significant of all of Aphrodite's lovers was Ares. But one night, the lovers tarried too long together. As Helius hitched up his golden chariot of the sun, he saw the lovers in Ares's palace in Thrace.<br>
<br>
When Helius told Hephaestus what he had seen, the smith god formed an unbreakable bronze net and secretly attached it to the posts and side of his bed. Then he bid aphrodite adieu, saying he was going to relax on Lemnos for a while.<br>
<br>
Of course, as soon as he had gone, Aphrodite sent for Ares. When the morning came, Hephaestus walked in, and found the two ensnared in the net. The cuckolded god quickly gathered all the other gods at his bedside to witness the shame of the naked and helpless couple and to heap ridiclue upon them.<br>
<br>
Hephaestus then demanded the return of the marriage gifts he had given to Zeus. But the ruler of the gods refused, calling the adultery a marital dispute and ridiculing Hephaestus as a fool fo rmaking it a public spectable.<br>
 ( Hermes and Apollo snickered that they would gladly make such a public spectacle if it meant lying with Aphrodite. )<br>
<br>
With his first glance at the nakid goddess, Poseidon fell in love with her. So the sea god suggested that Ares should pay for the marriage gifts, Poseidon gladly offered to serve as guarantor: If Ares defaulted on the payment, Poseidon would play the price and take Aphrodite as his own wife. Ares did ultimatly default on the debt, but Hephaestus-still smitten with his wife-did not really want a divorce at all, so he never brought it up again.<br>
<br>
Poseidon, however, was not that only god to envy Ares's position. Hermes too fell in love with naked Aphrodite. But when Aphrodite spurned his advances, Hermes sought the help of Zeus. The king of the gods dispatched an eagle to steal one of Aphrodite's sandles. To retrieve it, the goddess was forced to submit to Hermes. This union produced a double-sexed child: Hermaphroditus.<br>
<br>
Aphrodite also slept with the youngest of the gods, Dionysus. But Hera, who disapproved of Aphrodite's free ways, deformed their child Priapus. She made the boy incredibly ugly and endowed him with gargantuan genitles-an ironic comment on his mother's behavior. <p>Goddess Artemis
Protector of the Amazons
~*~Goddess of the hunt and the Moon~*~</p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top">  Page  <b>1</b> <a href=http://pub11.ezboard.com/famazonsunitefrm23.showMessageRange?topicID=160.topic&start=21&stop=24>2</a> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub11.ezboard.com/famazonsunitefrm23.showMessage?topicID=134.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub11.ezboard.com/famazonsunitefrm23.showMessage?topicID=178.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br></td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub11.ezboard.com/famazonsunitefrm23.emailToFriend?topicID=160.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub11.ezboard.com/famazonsunitefrm23.threadControl?topicID=160.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/blueMoon/deleteThread.jpg border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands (Moderator only)</a><br> <a href=http://pub11.ezboard.com/famazonsunitefrm23.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=160.topic>Subscribe</a> Click to receive email notification of replies<br>  <a href=http://pub11.ezboard.com/famazonsunitefrm23.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=160.topic>Unsubscribe</a> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies<br> </td><td align="right" valign="top"></td></tr><tr align="right"><td colspan=2><form action=http://pub11.ezboard.com/BBSForum.jumpShowForum method=post><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="1"><tr><td><b>jump to:</b><select name=forumName><option value="amazonsuniteamazonsunitescrollboard">Amazons Unite Scroll Board<option value="amazonsunitefrm32">The Mythical Odyssey<option value="amazonsunitefrm23">The Olympian Gods<option value="amazonsunitefrm15">Black Sea Tavern and Inn<option value="amazonsunitesistersofthemiscrya">Sisters of Themiscrya<option value="amazonsunitefrm6">Am